#import "template.typ": *

#let metadata = (
  title: "Effects of Controls",
  unit: "Group A (3-Axis) | Phase 1 — Lesson 1 | E1/E2",
  author: "C.Moroney",
  version: "v1.0.0",
)

#let lesson = (
title: [Effects of Controls]

,aim: [
Operate the primary and ancillary controls in flight, observe and describe their effects on the aircraft, and apply correct control technique and horizon referencing throughout.
]

,overview: [
Lesson 1 is the student's first flight. The theoretical foundation was covered in Lesson 0; this lesson covers the practical element. A brief theory review at the start confirms knowledge retention. The student taxis the aircraft for the first time under instructor guidance, then the instructor conducts the takeoff with the student following through on controls. In the training area, the instructor demonstrates each control effect in turn, then the student practises each one. The lesson also formally completes the remaining E1 practical competencies — taxiing, pre-start checks, and after-flight checks.

This lesson establishes the control technique habits, and horizon referencing discipline that every subsequent lesson builds on.
]

,learning_outcomes: [
#text(size:12pt)[*Knowledge*]
- Recall from previous lesson: axes, planes, primary effects, further effects, trim, power, flaps
- Explain why an aircraft inherently spirals, and the implications of positive dynamic stability
- Explain the importance of the pre-flight inspection, and perform one under instructor supervision
- Recall the required steps to complete the aircraft documentation

#text(size:12pt)[*Skills*]
- Taxi the aircraft using power, rudder pedals, and brakes; apply correct control positions throughout the taxi
- Apply smooth, positive, and coordinated control inputs to achieve a desired aircraft attitude (±10° pitch, ±30° roll)
- Observe and describe the primary and further effects of each control in flight
- Operate the trim to achieve hands-off level flight
- Identify the horizon as the primary attitude reference
- Identify parallax error from the left seat and correct for it

#text(size:12pt)[*Non-Technical Skills*]
- [SA] Monitor surrounding airspace; note other traffic; maintain awareness on the ground
- [TEM] Identify threats on the ground, during startup and taxi; verbalise at least one threat in the training area when prompted
- [HF] Identify parallax error from the left seat — horizon and instrument references will differ under certain circumstances; expect and correct for it
- [CRM] Apply correct control handover procedure throughout; hand over promptly and clearly; follow through on controls during demonstrations without adding input
]

,theory_knowledge: [
- Aircraft Attitude / Axes of Movement *(Pg 101, 102)* — revision from L0
- Primary Controls and Further Effects *(Pg 103–107)* — revision from L0
- Lift Augmentation and Trim *(Pg 126–131)* — revision from L0
- Human Factors — SA, TEM, parallax *(Pg 3, 13–16, 45)*
]

,ground_brief_topics: [
Total time: 20 minutes \
Equipment required: Aircraft model, whiteboard — keep this brief; the lesson is in the air \

*Theory Review from Lesson 0* (10 minutes)
- Quick verbal Q&A: primary effects of each control; further effects of ailerons and rudder; what trim does; what power does to pitch and yaw; wind correction positions for taxi
- This is not a re-teach — it confirms the homework was done and the knowledge is retained
- If a student cannot recall primary effects without prompting: extend the ground brief; do not proceed to flight until the foundation is solid

*Parallax Error and Horizon Referencing* (5 minutes)
- From the left seat, the visual horizon appears at a different angle than the right seat; a right turn will look shallower than a left turn for the same bank angle

*Non-Technical Skills for First Flight* (5 minutes)
- [TEM] On the ground: other aircraft, taxiing threats; In the training area: traffic, airspace boundaries
- [SA] Maintain awareness of traffic, maintain clear of cloud
- [CRM] Control handover; "I have control / You have control / follow me through"
- [HF] Parallax error in both the instruments, and in the sight picture from the left seat
]

,ground_tasks:[
#text(size:12pt)[*Instructor*]
- Review maintenance release with student; student identifies key items; instructor signs
- Check NOTAMs; brief relevant items
- Access NAIPS; student observes TAF/GAF/GPWT interpretation; notes major hazards

#text(size:12pt)[*Student*]
- Complete IMSAFE self-assessment and confirm fitness to fly
- Lead pre-flight inspection with instructor following
- Check documents folder; confirm all required documents present
- Set QNH from ATIS/AWIS or airfield elevation
- Complete the startup checklist under instructor guidance
- Taxi the aircraft to the runup area under instructor guidance — student has hands and feet on controls; instructor monitors and assists as needed
]

,in_flight_tasks:[
#text(size:12pt)[*E1/E2 Takeoff — Lesson 1*]
Instructor conducts the takeoff. Student follows through on controls throughout the ground roll, lift-off, and initial climb After-takeoff checks completed under instructor guidance.

#text(size:12pt)[*Demonstration*]
Instructor demonstrates each item in sequence, pattering the effect as it occurs. Student follows through on controls throughout each demonstration.

- *Stability*: Release controls in level flight during the transit to the training area; aircraft returns to level — positive pitch stability demonstrated; patter what is happening
- *Parallax*: Point out the difference in horizon appearance from the left seat; demonstrate a left and right 30° bank and describe how each looks from the left seat reference
- *Elevator*: Pitch to +10° — airspeed/RPM reduces; pitch to -10° — airspeed/RPM increases; demonstrate hands-off return toward trimmed attitude
- _*EMPHASISE* Airspeed is controlled with pitch_
- *Ailerons*: Roll left 30° — patter slip, show yaw and spiral tendency; return to wings level; repeat to the right
- *Rudder*: Yaw left — patter skid, show roll and spiral tendency; return to coordinated flight; repeat to the right
- *Trim*: Establish slow flight without trimming; demonstrate pressure required to overcome positive stability; demonstrate correct direction of trim input
- *Power*: While in slow flight, advance to full — nose pitches up, yaws and rolls left; correct roll to wings level; reduce to idle — nose pitches down, yaws and rolls right; patter each effect
- *Flaps*: Deploy, one stage at a time, to full — pitch effect; drag increase; power requirement; retract — pitch effect; patter each
- *Effect of Airspeed*: While in slow flight, student feels control effectiveness; increase airspeed (110 if able); student compares control effectiveness to earlier slow flight
- *Upset limits*: Demonstrate safe attitude limits in pitch; patter the horizon reference

#text(size:12pt)[*Student Practice*]
Student applies each control in turn. Do not over-prompt or assist on controls; allow the student to feel the effect.

- *Elevator*: Pitch to ±10°; hold and observe airspeed/RPM change; return to level
- *Ailerons*: Roll to ±30°; observe further effects; return to wings level
- *Rudder*: Apply yaw ±10°; observe further effects; return to coordinated
- *Power changes*: Advance to full; observe effects; return to cruise
- *Trim*: Set for cruise; achieve hands-off level flight; change power and hold attitude; re-trim; confirm correct direction
- *Flaps*: Deploy to first extension; observe pitch and power effects; retract; re-establish level flight
- *Scenario*: "Using only the further effects of the controls: 1. Pitch the nose up and down; 2. Roll left and right"
]

,common_errors:[
- *Overcontrolling*: Large inputs produce large responses — light grip on the controls; wine glass, not beer mug.
- *Fixating on instruments*: The horizon is the primary reference — instruments confirm, not set; prompt "look outside" immediately if the student starts fixating
- *Trim direction confused*: Reinforce from Lesson 0 every time a trim application is made.
- *Control position on taxi*: Instructor watches closely during the taxi; stick back during taxi.
]

,post_flight:[
- *Student Self-Assessment* (5 min): Student describes what they observed with each control; identifies which effect was most surprising or unclear.
- *Instructor Feedback* (10 min):
  - Evaluate control technique in the air: smooth, positive inputs, with correct control handover?
  - Review taxi technique: control position maintained? Speed appropriate?
  - Discuss one TEM threat identified during the flight.
  - Highlight: Stability will assist you in controlling the aircraft. Airspeed is controlled with pitch. Power produces yaw.
- *Next Steps*: Assign homework. Preview Lesson 2 (Straight and Level): the PAT and LARI workcycle.
]

,standards_for_progression:[
#text(size:12pt)[*Progressing (P) — may advance to Lesson 2*]
- *Taxi*: Completes taxi with instructor guidance; controls positioned correctly with prompting; speed and directional control reasonable
- *Control inputs*: Overcontrolling present but reducing; no persistent opposite inputs; technique improving
- *Theory recall*: Names primary effects of all controls without prompting; describes further effects of ailerons and rudder with minor prompting
- *Trim*: Applies trim in correct direction; approaching hands-off result
- *Lookout*: Beginning to maintain lookout scan between tasks
- *Airmanship*: Completes IMSAFE; verbalises one TEM threat when prompted
#text(size:12pt)[*Solo Standard (S) — required before first solo*]
- *Taxi*: Completes taxi with minimal instructor guidance; controls positioned correctly; speed and directional control good
- *Control inputs*: All correct in direction and magnitude
- *Theory recall*: Names primary effects of all controls without prompting; describes further effects of ailerons and rudder with minor prompting
- *Trim*: Applies trim in correct direction; with hands-off result
- *Lookout*: Beginning to maintain lookout scan between tasks
- *Airmanship*: Completes IMSAFE; verbalises one TEM threat when prompted

- *Outcome*: Recorded as P, S or NC with specific comments. NC requires an additional Lesson 1 session before Lesson 2 commences.
]

,safety:[
- *Weather*: Horizon clearly visible; ceiling >2000 ft AGL; surface wind \<25 knots
- *Altitude*: Conduct all in-flight exercises above 1500 ft AGL; instructor pre-selects forced landing area
- *TEM*:
  - This is the first flight — expect possible overwhelm; pause, allow reorientation, and continue at a pace matched to the student
  - Monitor for student anxiety or air sickness, address immediately and return if required
  - Do not rush through the demonstration sequence — one control at a time, full student understanding before the next
  - Monitor traffic throughout; maintain SA regarding controlled airspace
- *Aircraft Limits*: Demonstrate all control effects gently and progressively
]

,homework:[
- Read Bob Tait's RAAus Study Guide:
  - Controls: Pg 101–107 (revise all effects observed in today's flight)
  - Aerodynamics: Pg 110–118 (aerofoils, lift generation, control surface effects)
  - Human Factors: Pg 3, 13–16, 45 (LARI scan, TEM, SA, IMSAFE)
- Prepare for Lesson 2 (Straight and Level):
  - Performance: Pg 146–147 (airspeed indicator, altimeter)
  - Air Legislation: Pg 71–72 (VMC requirements, right-of-way)
- Reflect:
  - "During the flight, which control had the most noticeable further effect? Describe what you observed."
  - "If I wanted to slow down without climbing, what control inputs would I need and why?"
  - "What were the taxi wind corrections for today's conditions?"
]
)

#show: body => lesson_plan(metadata, lesson, body)